name.text: Finding Complementary Angles and Trigonometric Ratios

questiontext.text:
Angles \({@letter_1@}\) and \({@letter_2@}\) are complementary. If \( {@letter_1@}\) = {@fraction@}\({@letter_2@}\) , calculate the following:

  1. Find the values of the angles:

    1. \({@letter_1@}=\)[[input:ans1]]\(^\circ\) [[validation:ans1]]
    2. \({@letter_2@}=\)[[input:ans2]]\(^\circ\)[[validation:ans2]]

      3. [[feedback:prt1]]

  2. Using a calculator, find the following correct to four significant figures:

    1. \(\sin\, {@letter_1@}=\)[[input:ans3]][[validation:ans3]]
    2. \(\cos\,{@letter_2@}=\)[[input:ans4]] [[validation:ans4]]

      3. [[feedback:prt2]]

generalfeedback.text:
When we say {@letter_1@} and {@letter_2@} are complementary, it implies that \({@letter_1@}+{@letter_2@}=90^\circ\).
Also, we have \({@letter_1@}={@fraction@}{@letter_2@}\).

First, write \({@letter_1@}\) in terms of \({@letter_2@}\), that is,
\({@eq_1@}
{@eq_2@}

Since \({@letter_1@}+{@letter_2@}=90^\circ\), substitute \({@eq_2@}\):
\({@frac_2*letter_1@}+{@letter_1@}=90\)
{@eq_5@}
\(\quad {@letter_1@}=\frac{90}{{@coeficient@}}\)
\(\qquad ={@Ta_1@}\)

Therefore,

  1. \(\angle \,{@letter_1@}={@Ta_1@}^\circ\)

  2. \(\angle\,{@letter_2@}\)

    \(\begin{align} \angle \,{@letter_2@}&=90-{@Ta_1@}^\circ\\ &={@Ta_2@}^\circ \end{align}\)

Use your calculator to find both \(\sin\,{@Ta_1@}^\circ\) and \(\cos\,{@Ta_1@}^\circ\), and write the answers correct to 4 significant figures.
Therefore,

  1. \(\sin\,{@Ta_1@}^\circ={@an_1@}\)
  2. \(\cos\,{@Ta_2@}^\circ={@an_2@}\)

questionnote.text:
Part a of the question

\(\angle \,{@letter_1@}={@Ta_1@}^\circ\)

\(\angle \,{@letter_2@}={@Ta_2@}^\circ\)

Part b of the question

\(\sin\,{@letter_1@}={@an_1@}\)

\(\cos\,{@letter_1@}={@an_2@}\)
